fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let (S \triangleright  P, \iota ^S, \sigma ^S, \text {pr}^S) and (T \triangleright  Q, \iota ^T, \sigma ^T, \text {pr}^T) be monad containers.
  A distributive law of S \triangleright  P over T \triangleright  Q is given by the data:
       \begin {align*}       &u_1 : \prod _{s : S} (P\ s \to  T) \to  T \\       &u_2 : \prod _{s : S} \prod _{f : P\ s \to  T} Q\ (u_1\ s\ f) \to  S \\       &v_1 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (u_1\ s\ f)} P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q) \to  P\ s \\       &v_2 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (u_1\ s\ f)} \prod _{p : P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)} Q\ (f\ (v_1\ q\ p)) \\     \end {align*}   
  where the following equalities hold:
       \begin {align*}       u\ \iota ^S\ (\lambda  \_ . t) &= (t , \lambda  \_ . \iota ^S)\\       u\ s\ (\lambda  \_. \iota ^T) &= (\iota ^T , \lambda  \_. s)\\       v\ \{\iota ^S\}\ \{\lambda  \_. t\} &= \langle  \pi _2 , \pi _1 \rangle \\       v\ \{s\}\ \{\lambda  \_. \iota ^T\} &= \langle  \pi _2 , \pi _1 \rangle \\       \\        u_1\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ f)\ (g \circ  \text {pr}^S) &= u_1\ s\ (u_1 \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle )\\       u_2\ (\sigma ^S\ s\ f)\ (g \circ  \text {pr}^S) &= \sigma ^S \circ  \langle  u_2\ s\ (u_1 \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle ) , (u_2 \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle ) \circ  v \rangle \\         \text {pr}^S_1\ (v_1\ q\ p) &= v_1\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p)\\       \text {pr}^S_2\ (v_1\ q\ p) &= v_1\ (v_2\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p)) \ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\\       v_2\ q\ p &= v_2\ (v_2\ q\ (\text {pr}^S_1\ p))\ (\text {pr}^S_2\ p)\\       \\       u_1\ s\ (\sigma ^T \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle ) &= \sigma ^T\ (u_1\ s\ f, u_1 \circ  \langle  u_2\ s\ f , g \circ  v \rangle )\\       u_2\ s\ (\sigma ^T \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle ) &= (u_2 \circ  \langle  u_2\ s\ f , g \circ  v \rangle ) \circ  \text {pr}^T\\       v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p) &= v_1\ q\ p\\       v_2\ (\text {pr}^T_1\ q)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p) &= \text {pr}^T_1\ (v_2\ q\ p)\\       v_2\ (\text {pr}^T_2\ q)\ p &= \text {pr}^T_2\ (v_2\ q\ p)     \end {align*}   
  We use the notation \langle  f , g \rangle  := \lambda  x . (f\ x , g\ x), and liberal use of currying and uncurrying.
